          "body": "The poem shifts at verse 17 into first-person plural — the community speaks. 'Yet our eyes failed, looking for help was useless; in our watching we have watched for a nation that could not save.' The nation in view is almost certainly Egypt — the recurrent temptation of Judah's kings, consistently condemned by the prophets (Isa. 30:1-7; 31:1; Jer. 37:7). Eyes strained toward the southwestern horizon saw no relief column coming. Then verse 20 names the deeper failure: the community had placed messianic trust in the Davidic king — 'the breath of our nostrils, the LORD's anointed' — as the one under whose shadow they would live among the nations. The capture of Zedekiah (2 Kings 25:4-7) exposed that trust as misplaced. The anointed was a type, not the antitype; a shadow of the coming Christ, not the substance. The community's grief in 4:20 is not merely political — it is theological disorientation. The human king cannot be the breath of life. Howard Hendricks was right that the Christian's most dangerous idols are the good ones — anointed things substituted for the Anointed One."
